[
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi everyone, I am reading a paper with the following claim and I don't see how to prove it. I guess it should be simple as it is not justified by anything.<br>\nLet <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F : \\mathcal A \\to \\mathcal B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span> be an identity-on-object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>-functor between small <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>-categories, then the functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>F</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>:</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[F, 1] : [\\mathcal B, \\mathcal V] \\to [\\mathcal A, \\mathcal V]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> has a left adjoint and strictly creates colimits.<br>\nI understand <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>F</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[F, 1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> as doing the following on objects : <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>∘</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\mapsto X \\circ F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>, I hope this is the right thing.<br>\nDoes someone knows how this works ? Thank you in advance !</p>",
        "id": 512551024,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Jourde",
        "timestamp": 1744809381
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The left adjoint should be \"left Kan extension along <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> \", so you need some conditions on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{V}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> for that to exist</p>",
        "id": 512551312,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1744809477
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They work with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> that are locally presentable, would that be enough ? I don't think they have any other assumptions<br>\nIs 4.1 in <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Kan+extension\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Kan+extension</a> what you are refering to ?</p>",
        "id": 512553351,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Jourde",
        "timestamp": 1744810023
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, because locally presentable categories are cocomplete, which is enough.</p>",
        "id": 512557878,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Speight",
        "timestamp": 1744811194
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think you also need a smallness condition that is also verified by lfp categories, otherwise I agree.</p>",
        "id": 512561274,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1744812077
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You only need the size condition on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> (for which <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span></span></span></span> being small is enough). Local presentability is not necessary.</p>",
        "id": 512568708,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1744813906
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(But cocompleteness is, which they’re getting from local presentability.)</p>",
        "id": 512573886,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1744815240
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you everyone for your answers. Indeed, corollary X.3.2 in Mac Lane says (if I reverse it to left extensions) that I need <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span></span></span></span> to be small and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> to be cocomplete</p>",
        "id": 512574744,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Jourde",
        "timestamp": 1744815451
    },
